  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Designing Storage Strategies**\n\nI\'m now focusing on designing the full-stack application and determining the best storage strategy. I\'m exploring dashboard session logging specifically. Initially, I considered `localStorage`, but my research now strongly points towards a secure, cloud-hosted database per \"Storage & Persistence\" guidelines.\n\n\n**Analyzing Persistence Tradeoffs**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the nuances of persistence. Considering the teacher dashboard in AI Studio, local storage seems acceptable for demo profiles and historical runs if client-side, but I\'m weighing server-side session logging or an in-memory database as alternatives. The \"Durable Cloud Persistence\" guideline points to Firestore, but if selected, there must be a `set_up_firebase` call with a UI step to accept Firestore terms that could slow the flow.\n\n\n**Evaluating Persistence Models**\n\nI\'ve been evaluating persistence models and have landed on using a local JSON file database on the server, specifically `./data/sessions.json` or `./data/students.json`. This approach offers a robust, 100% working solution out-of-the-box, without requiring any external project provisioning. I\'m building out a model for this locally inside `./server.ts`. This seems to be the most durable and performant solution.\n\n\n**Defining Log Structure**\n\nI\'ve defined the log structure for student interactions. We will track `raw_input`, `edited_version`, `skill_mastery_focus`, and `engagement_score`. I\'m starting to design the student interface, which will feature a warm, high-energy animated character, either \"Coach Voicey\" or \"Luna the Literacy Lion.\"\n\n\n**Implementing Voice Integration**\n\nI\'m now implementing voice integration. If speech recognition isn\'t available, I\'ll gracefully provide a text input prompt: \"Or, type your idea here!\" For voice playback, I plan to leverage `window.speechSynthesis` for an immersive experience. I envision a toggle labeled \"\360\237\224\212 Read Aloud\" with voice options, making the coach\'s replies a spoken response.\n\n\n**Designing Student Interface**\n\nI\'m now focusing on designing the student interface, with interactive elements. I\'m exploring interactive dropzones, button selectors, and editable inputs with guide highlights. The \"Name Game\" will have highlighted proper nouns for capitalization. \"Word Upgrade\" will feature highlighted words that can be swapped for \"Juicy Words.\" \"Evidence Check\" encourages speaking or writing reasons.\n\nI\'m also working on a \"Frustration Detector\" with a \"Feeling Stuck?\" button that provides simplification, hints, or collaboration. Celebration effects with confetti animations and earned badges like \"Punctuation Pioneer\" are also planned. I\'m starting to think about a separate, secure view for the Teacher Dashboard interface.\n\n\n**Defining Teacher Dashboard**\n\nI\'m now defining the structure of the \"Teacher Mode\" dashboard. It will have a passcode or toggle, styled in a professional aesthetic. Key sections are \"Class Overview\" with metrics, an \"Active Student List,\" and \"Session Logs & Timeline\" that provides a searchable view of completed sessions. The timeline displays input, edited versions, focus, and scores, along with a Gemini-powered session analysis. It also includes lesson customization tools.\n\n\n**Implementing Server Code**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in implementing the server code within `server.ts`. I\'m focusing on the API calls to `/api/chat`, integrating Gemini, specifically using the `@google/genai` library and `gemini-3.5-flash` model. I\'ve paused momentarily to confirm the Express server configuration, ensuring robust functionality. The server will initialize on port 3000, host `0.0.0.0`, and integrate Vite for development and serve static files for production. The API endpoint will handle chat history, student input, scaffolding state, and task focus, passing it to Gemini, instructed to embody \"Voice2Literacy,\" a 4th-grade coach. I\'m now writing and testing it.\n\n\n**Structuring API Responses**\n\nI\'m now structuring API responses. I\'ve defined a JSON object with key fields: `coachReply`, `detectedTask`, `highlightedText`, `suggestedCorrections`, and the dynamically updated `sessionLog`. I\'m also including a `frustrated` flag. I\'m focusing on `/api/sessions` endpoints for the Teacher Dashboard: `GET` to retrieve logs, `POST` to save logs, and `DELETE` to remove them. I\'ll also implement a `GET /api/students` endpoint. I\'ll seed `./data/sessions.json` with sample data.\n\n\n**Drafting Server Implementation**\n\nI\'m now drafting `server.ts` in the project root, focusing on robust file structure and database management. I\'ll dynamically write to `./data/sessions.json` with in-memory backups. Confirmed the `@google/genai` dependency and `tsconfig.json` configurations. I\'ve confirmed that the skill documentation suggests using `gemini-3.5-flash`.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create the full-stack server file `server.ts` using Express and Vite. It will feature:\n1. Lazy initialization of the Gemini API SDK (`@google/genai`) to handle any missing keys gracefully without crashing on startup.\n2. A high-fidelity AI coaching chat endpoint `/api/chat` using `gemini-3.5-flash` to act as the supportive 4th-grade tutor, diagnose student text, scaffold tasks, and assess performance.\n3. Persistent file-based API endpoints for saving and retrieving session logs in `/api/sessions` and student rosters in `/api/students`.\n4. Pre-seeded demo records so the Teacher Dashboard looks realistic and ready out-of-the-box.\n5. Automated Vite middleware in development and static bundle serving in production."
