    thinking: "**Considering Speech Recognition**\n\nI\'m now focusing on speech recognition for the `StudentCoach.tsx` component. I\'m exploring the HTML5 Web Speech API, using the typical check for `SpeechRecognition` implementation to ensure browser compatibility. This will ensure my work is compatible with both webkit and standard APIs. This seems to be the most common and robust approach.\n\n\n**Implementing Speech and Text**\n\nI\'m now thinking about how to handle scenarios where speech recognition isn\'t available. A fallback text input will be implemented: \"Or type your idea here!\" I\'ll ensure both options are unified, and offer a simple click-to-speak or text box approach. I\'m also planning to implement text-to-speech using `window.speechSynthesis` for the coach\'s responses, ideally a friendly, high-pitched voice if it\'s available.\n\n\n**Adding Avatar Animations**\n\nI\'m now integrating an avatar animation to visually represent the coach speaking, such as mouth movements or other visual cues. My focus is also on a \"Read Aloud\" toggle for text-to-speech to engage younger users. I\'m excited about this, as it makes the tool more fun for kids! I\'m also planning the user flow!\n\n\n**Designing Interactive Activities**\n\nI\'m now focusing on interactive activities for the student. I will make a scaffold panel where students can visually edit suggestions or input corrections via voice or text. When a student is stuck, the coach will offer support with big friendly options. I will reward correct responses with animations and celebrations like confetti, badges and joyful expressions!\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/components/StudentCoach.tsx`, a kid-friendly speech coaching interface where students can:\n1. Choose their student profile and avatar.\n2. Select an active literacy scaffolding focus (e.g., \"The Name Game\", \"The Stop Sign\").\n3. Use the browser\'s Web Speech API (`webkitSpeechRecognition` / `SpeechRecognition`) to speak their ideas live with real-time feedback, or use the accessible keyboard typing box as a fallback.\n4. Interact with the custom-designed \"Coach Voicey\" cartoon avatar who bounces, smiles, and reads guidance aloud using browser SpeechSynthesis.\n5. Tap on automated high-contrast hint options for \"Surgical Edits\" (like capitalizing proper nouns or replacing flat words with juicy alternatives).\n6. Pivot to a \"Confidence Booster\" hint mode if they get stuck.\n7. Celebrate with interactive badge ceremonies and save their session progress to the teacher logs."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 5
      nanos: 795226519
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
