  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Error Handling**\n\nI\'ve been examining the error handling strategy within `/api/chat`. Currently, any errors encountered during the Gemini API call trigger a fallback response, indicated by a 500 status code. This means the system always attempts to provide a response, even in failure scenarios. I need to understand if this fallback behavior is optimal or if we need more granular error analysis and responses.\n\n\n**Refining Error Responses**\n\nI\'m now diving deeper into the specifics of the fallback mechanism. I\'m noting the structured data provided when an error triggers the fallback, including the coach reply, focus suggestions, and scaffold details. This is the new detail! Specifically, I see how a child-friendly response is crafted, with attention to engagement and sub-skill focus, and how this relates to logging.\n\n\n**Addressing Client-Side Errors**\n\nI\'ve discovered a critical issue: the `StudentCoach` component, along with `logCompletedSession` and `handleSendEdit`, lack proper error handling for non-OK responses from the `/api/chat` endpoint. This means 500 status codes are currently unmanaged. I\'m focusing on implementing client-side error handling to parse the JSON response from `/api/chat` and utilize the `fallback` response, if available, for a more graceful degradation. I\'m taking the 503 error, potentially caused by high demand for Gemini 3.5 Flash, into consideration.\n\n\n**Evaluating Fallback Strategy**\n\nI\'m now weighing the pros and cons of two approaches. I\'m leaning toward allowing the backend to return a 200 status with the child-friendly fallback response, along with a flag, enabling seamless client-side operation during API issues. This ensures the app continues working without crashing, even if there\'s a problem with Gemini. I\'m also considering adding a retry mechanism for enhanced resilience.\n\n\n**Exploring Model Fallbacks**\n\nI\'m now implementing a new fallback strategy for the Gemini model. My goal is to use `gemini-3.5-flash` first. If it fails, I\'ll retry with `gemini-3.1-flash-lite`, using the offline fallback only as a last resort. This should enhance robustness during service disruptions, while still giving a great response.\n\n\n**Implementing Client Grace**\n\nI\'m now focusing on client-side improvements. By returning a 200 status code with the fallback object and a flag like `isFallback: true`, the client can subtly indicate a problem or allow students to continue their experience seamlessly. I\'m verifying that the client, specifically `StudentCoach.tsx`, handles errors gracefully, and investigating its `handleSendIdea` implementation.\n\n\n**Improving Error Handling**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing enhanced error handling within `StudentCoach.tsx`. Specifically, I\'m focusing on managing non-OK responses from `/api/chat`. I\'m going to display a child-friendly error message, like \"The Coach is taking a little rest right now! Let\'s try again in a moment,\" or seamlessly fall back to a local response. This way, the student experience remains uninterrupted.\n\n\n**Refining Status Codes**\n\nI\'m now implementing logic to return a 200 status with the fallback, if available, for a resilient experience. I can either use `data.fallback` or `data` directly, depending on the server response structure. I am also planning on adding a boolean flag like `isFallback: true` or `offlineMode: true` to the returned JSON, so the frontend can display child-friendly messaging. I\'ll need to update the server\'s catch block to facilitate this approach, so that `StudentCoach.tsx` can handle this gracefully, while avoiding a status 500 error.\n\n\n**Optimizing API Fallbacks**\n\nI\'m now refining the model fallback strategy for `/api/chat`. The new process is: try `gemini-3.5-flash`, then `gemini-3.1-flash-lite`, and finally use the offline fallback. The key is now to return a 200 status with the fallback JSON, including an `isOfflineFallback: true` flag. I\'ll add a