    thinking: "**Designing Fallback Mechanism**\n\nI\'ve made good progress. `types.ts` is solid. My focus has shifted to designing a robust fallback in `server.ts`. The initial plan is to use `gemini-3.5-flash` first, but I need to make sure I\'m catching errors and retrying appropriately within the `server.ts` file.\n\n\n**Implementing Fallback Function**\n\nI\'m now focused on implementing a robust `generateContentWithFallback` function in `server.ts`. I\'ve started examining the existing API call (lines 319-361). The goal is to encapsulate the retry logic and fallback model selection. I\'m thinking of creating a helper function for this. I\'ll need to handle the `try...catch` block gracefully.\n\n\n**Verifying Fallback Strategy**\n\nI\'ve tested the fallback to `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` and confirmed it supports the required `responseSchema`. I verified its validity, noting its presence in `SKILL.md`. I\'m now contemplating additional fallback models beyond `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` if that fails. Specifically, I\'m considering `gemini-2.5-flash` as a potential third option.\n\n\n**Refining Error Handling**\n\nI\'m now refining the error handling. Considering that `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` is fast and reliable, the primary fallback strategy now focuses on it, after attempting `gemini-3.5-flash`. I\'m planning to handle failures gracefully. If both fail, I\'ll return a child-friendly fallback response with a 200 status. I\'m adding `isFallback: true` to the response to inform the client. I\'ve realized changing `res.status(500)` to `res.status(200)` is crucial in the catch block for `/api/chat`.\n\n\n**Evaluating Third-Tier Fallback**\n\nI\'m now evaluating a third-tier fallback model, considering the potential scenarios if both `gemini-3.5-flash` and `gemini-3.1-flash-lite` fail. I\'m exploring the feasibility of using a smaller model, potentially even a local one, for handling extremely rare edge cases. I need to make sure this local fallback also supports a response compatible with the responseSchema. I\'m prioritizing minimal resource usage here.\n\n\n**Dynamically Building Fallback**\n\nI\'m now focused on dynamically constructing the fallback content based on `req.body`. I\'ve identified `focusType` within `req.body`, which is a key factor. I\'m building `suggestedFocus`, `scaffoldType`, and `hints` based on the value of `focusType`. I will make sure the fallback adapts to the session\'s specific needs using conditional logic.\n\n\n**Adapting Fallback Logic**\n\nI\'m now integrating logic for the `feedback` stage within the fallback mechanism. Specifically, I\'m setting `isActivityCompleted: true` on the second turn, when in fallback mode, to allow the child to successfully finish the activity. This helps them earn their badge and avoid getting stuck. The goal is to ensure they can proceed in this scenario, even when the primary models fail. The conditional logic is now being adjusted to account for `stage === \"feedback\"` and determine when to update `isActivityCompleted`.\n\n\n**Finalizing Fallback Mechanism**\n\nI\'ve finalized the two-turn scaffolding experience. The fallback now provides a seamless experience for the child, even offline. The \"initiate\" stage celebrates the child\'s idea. The \"feedback\" stage completes the activity, logs the session, and awards the badge, all with status 200, making it feel functional. The logging note explains the graceful fallback. I\'ve confirmed it works.\n\n\n"
